    <h2>Why Humanize AI-Generated Content?</h2>
    <div style="margin-bottom: 24px;">
      <div style="background: white; border: 1px solid var(--border); padding: 20px; margin-bottom: 14px;">
        <p><strong>Google quality signals</strong></p>
        <p>Google's Helpful Content Update and subsequent quality rater guidelines emphasize natural, helpful content. AI-generated text often follows predictable patterns — similar sentence lengths, repetitive transitions, and formal constructions that readers and algorithms recognize as non-human. Humanized text varies these patterns, improving engagement metrics like time on page and scroll depth that Google uses as indirect ranking signals.</p>
      </div>
      <div style="background: white; border: 1px solid var(--border); padding: 20px; margin-bottom: 14px;">
        <p><strong>Reader trust and engagement</strong></p>
        <p>Readers engage more with content that feels personal and authentic. Studies from Nielsen Norman Group show that conversational, human-sounding copy has 23% higher engagement rates than formal, robotic text. When readers feel like a real person is talking to them, they spend more time on the page, share more often, and convert at higher rates.</p>
      </div>
      <div style="background: white; border: 1px solid var(--border); padding: 20px; margin-bottom: 14px;">
        <p><strong>Platform compliance</strong></p>
        <p>LinkedIn, Medium, and other publishing platforms are increasingly flagging AI-generated content. Humanized text reduces the risk of automated flags and algorithmic suppression. For email marketing, human-sounding copy consistently outperforms AI-generated text in open rates and click-through rates because it avoids spam-trigger patterns.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

