    <h2>Tone Guide — When to Use Each</h2>
    <div style="margin-bottom: 24px;">
      <div style="background: white; border: 1px solid var(--border); padding: 20px; margin-bottom: 14px;">
        <p><strong>Conversational (default)</strong></p>
        <p>Best for: Blog posts, newsletters, podcasts, YouTube scripts, and any content where you want to sound like you are talking directly to the reader. Uses "you" and "I," asks rhetorical questions, and feels like a coffee shop conversation. This is the safest default for most web content.</p>
      </div>
      <div style="background: white; border: 1px solid var(--border); padding: 20px; margin-bottom: 14px;">
        <p><strong>Casual</strong></p>
        <p>Best for: Lifestyle brands, consumer products, social media captions, and content targeting younger audiences (Gen Z, millennials). Uses contractions, colloquialisms, and an easygoing energy. Think of how a friendly barista would explain something — warm, approachable, not trying too hard.</p>
      </div>
      <div style="background: white; border: 1px solid var(--border); padding: 20px; margin-bottom: 14px;">
        <p><strong>Professional</strong></p>
        <p>Best for: B2B content, consulting, SaaS, financial services, legal, and corporate communications. Polished and authoritative without being stiff. Sounds like a confident expert who knows their field inside out. Sentences are well-structured but not robotic. Good for white papers, case studies, and thought leadership.</p>
      </div>
      <div style="background: white; border: 1px solid var(--border); padding: 20px; margin-bottom: 14px;">
        <p><strong>Academic</strong></p>
        <p>Best for: Research papers, educational content, technical documentation, and medical/scientific writing. Formal, precise, and well-structured. Uses complete sentences and avoids contractions. Maintains objectivity while remaining readable. Ideal when credibility and precision matter more than engagement.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

